Posted: Sun May 06, 2012 4:36 am
All of these should be available for instant streaming on Netflix.Ink: A low-budget film where there are a few occasional mishaps that draw attention to the fact. I don't think they end up detracting too heavily, though. There are some well-choreographed fights that took me by surprise as a lot of the style and themes are oneiric.Lo: This is even lower-budget than Ink and a lot of the visual quirkiness comes from the fact that it was originally a play. I found the gestalt captivating for what's essentially a dialogue.I didn't see any Korean movies in your list so here are three you might like.Oldboy: I couldn't find an official trailer and the iconic scenes don't work well out of context anyway. Of these, this one is probably closest to what you want for quirky with a lot of visual flair as it has the budget to realize the action. The rest of Park's thematic revenge trilogy is also worth checking out if you find you like this.Mother: The chiastic opening and ending scenes are my favorites. For something slower-paced and dramatic, there's actually a few impactful action scenes.The Host: A hilarious near spoof of the monster movie. There's quite a lot of symbolism and the obvious themes (environmentalism, nationalism) whose presentations grated at first grew on me as the drama developed.
