Posted: Mon May 07, 2012 8:04 am
Twelve wrote:Zanshin wrote:2001: A Space Odyssey. If you haven't seen one of the all time sci-fi classics, you should watch it. I saw it for the first time a few years back, and it's one of the few movies where when the credits rolled, I went "fuuuuuuuck. I liked it, but I don't know what the fuck I just saw."It's funny how well this reaction tends to hold up on repeated viewings. Once humans show up, the plot progresses in a very understandable way, until it doesn't. So you're left feeling, "I know I wasn't really supposed to understand that, but I thought that I did for a while."Occasionally I'll notice cross connections between things that blow my mind. I was watching some episodes of the documentary series called The Universe (available on Netflix streaming), and they were discussing the current understanding of our solar system, and how it relates to Jupiter. Most star systems that resemble ours tend to be dual star systems, however ours isn't. Stars are basically giant balls of hydrogen gas, where the mass causes enough pressure that nuclear fusion takes place (fusing hydrogen into helium). If a star doesn't have enough pressure to create fusion, it becomes a brown dwarf. Brown dwarves are 13 to 80 times the mass of Jupiter. Jupiter itself is simply a giant ball of hydrogen gas with no solid core. So since Jupiter, brown dwarves, and stars have the exact same makeup, with their only difference being mass, some researchers argue that Jupiter is really a failed brown dwarf, which in turn is a failed star. Spoiler: show
Then I remembered the ending of 2010: The Year We Make Contact. My mind == blown.
You know what? My next recommendation is a documentary. The Universe.
